<article>
    <h1>What to watch</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201225/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-25"><time>2020-12-25</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE STYLE WEEKEND</span>
        - <span role="byline">John Lui&#xD;&#xA;Film Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent&#xD;&#xA;john&#xAD;lui@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Joe Gard­ner, voiced by Jamie Foxx, is a mu­sic teacher who yearns to play pro­fes­sion­ally, with a jazz out­fit. His life is cut short as he is on the verge of achiev­ing his goal. Un­will­ing to go to his eter­nal rest, he fi­na­gles his way to another di­men­sion, the Great Be­fore, where freshly minted souls are pre­pared for life on Earth. He meets 22, voiced by Tina Fey, an Earth-avoid­ing trou­ble­maker who has sab­o­taged ev­ery at­tempt at be­ing born into a hu­man body.</p>
    <p>You will not be sur­prised to learn that di­rec­tor and co-writer Pete Doc­ter worked on In­side Out (2015), a film that, like Soul, turns ab­stract con­cepts into char­ac­ters. Here, as in the pre­vi­ous film, the adora­bil­ity fac­tor is high, helped along by tal­ent such as Bri­tish ac­tor Richard Ayoade, who plays a be­fore-life coun­sel­lor with the cheer­i­ness of a chil­dren’s tele­vi­sion-show host.</p>
    <p>Coun­sel­lors like him in­habit a weird yet fully formed spir­i­tual di­men­sion; cre­at­ing a uni­verse from scratch has al­ways been a Pixar strength. With the help of co-writer and co-di­rec­tor Kemp Pow­ers, the earthly world of New York’s black neigh­bour­hoods also comes to vi­brant life, giv­ing this story of what it means to find joy the firm ground it needs.</p>

